06613nam a22011655i 9780691216652DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020040045  a9780691216652  a(DE-B1597)573236  a(OCoLC)1253313282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aU163b.B532 2021 4aU163 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a355.02/182231 aBiddle, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNonstate Warfare :bThe Military Methods of Guerillas, Warlords, and Militias /cStephen Biddle. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b16 b&w illus. 6 tables. 7 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tMaps -- tPreface -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Fallacy of Guerilla Warfare -- t3 Materially Optimal Behavior -- t4 Politically Achievable Behavior -- t5 Hezbollah in the 2006 Lebanon Campaign -- t6 The Jaish al Mahdi in Iraq, 2003–8 -- t7 The Somali National Alliance in Somalia, 1992–94 -- t8 The ZNG, HV, and SVK in the Croatian Wars of Independence, 1991–95 -- t9 The Vietcong in the Second Indochina War, 1965–68 -- t10 Conclusion and Implications -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow nonstate military strategies overturn traditional perspectives on warfareSince September 11th, 2001, armed nonstate actors have received increased attention and discussion from scholars, policymakers, and the military. Underlying debates about nonstate warfare and how it should be countered is one crucial assumption: that state and nonstate actors fight very differently. In Nonstate Warfare, Stephen Biddle upturns this distinction, arguing that there is actually nothing intrinsic separating state or nonstate military behavior. Through an in-depth look at nonstate military conduct, Biddle shows that many nonstate armies now fight more "conventionally" than many state armies, and that the internal politics of nonstate actors—their institutional maturity and wartime stakes rather than their material weapons or equipment—determines tactics and strategies.Biddle frames nonstate and state methods along a continuum, spanning Fabian-style irregular warfare to Napoleonic-style warfare involving massed armies, and he presents a systematic theory to explain any given nonstate actor’s position on this spectrum. Showing that most warfare for at least a century has kept to the blended middle of the spectrum, Biddle argues that material and tribal culture explanations for nonstate warfare methods do not adequately explain observed patterns of warmaking. Investigating a range of historical examples from Lebanon and Iraq to Somalia, Croatia, and the Vietcong, Biddle demonstrates that viewing state and nonstate warfighting as mutually exclusive can lead to errors in policy and scholarship.A comprehensive account of combat methods and military rationale, Nonstate Warfare offers a new understanding for wartime military behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAsymmetric warfarevCase studies. 0aGuerrilla warfarevCase studies. 0aMilitiavCase studies. 0aNon-state actors (International relations)vCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAdmiral Jonathan Howe.  aAndrea Dew.  aCroatian Wars of Independence.  aFabian.  aHV.  aHezbollah.  aInsurgents, Terrorists and Militias.  aJAM.  aJaish al-Mahdi.  aMilitias.  aNapoleonic.  aSNA.  aSVK.  aSecond Indochina War.  aSeth Jones.  aSomali National Alliance.  aStathis Kalyvas.  aThe Logic of Violence in Civil Warfare.  aWaging Insurgent Warfare.  aZNG.  aasy